4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in LinuxBudgie is a modern approach to the desktop experience. You can further enhance it to your liking with these customization tips. https://itsfoss.com/budgie-customization/ 64f04e50287fcb04eb66819c Customization ⚙️Sagar Sharma Thu, 28 Sep 2023 03:07:32 GMT <img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/budgie-customisation-guide.png" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux"><p> If you ask me to make the MATE desktop modernized with added features and GTK support, I may come up with something like Budgie!</p><p> Budgie is an impressive desktop environment (DE) that provides you with a familiar layout along with a unique user experience.</p><p> So, how can you customize the Budgie desktop to elevate your experience? Fret not; I got your back here with some essential tips to tweak your Budgie experience.</p><p> I will help you do the following:</p><ul><li> <strong>Change wallpaper</strong></li><li> <strong>Change themes, icons, and cursor (the easy way)</strong></li><li> <strong>Customize panel</strong></li><li> <strong>Customize dock</strong></li></ul><p> Let us get started! 🤩</p><h2 id="1-change-the-wallpaper-of-budgie-de"> 1. Change the wallpaper of Budgie DE</h2><p> The Budgie desktop comes with some beautiful wallpapers pre-installed.</p><p> To change the wallpaper on Budgie&#39;s desktop, all you have to do is follow two simple steps:</p><ol><li> Right-click on the home screen and choose <code>Change Desktop Backgroun</code> option</li><li> Select the image, and it will be applied to your home screen </li></ol><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/08/Change-wallpaper.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1776" height="1116" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/08/Change-wallpaper.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/08/Change-wallpaper.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1600/2023/08/Change-wallpaper.png 1600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/08/Change-wallpaper.png 1776w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Click to enlarge the image</span></figcaption></figure><p> But if you don&#39;t like the available options, you can always download wallpapers from the web.</p><p> Once done, open the file manager, navigate to where the image is located, right-click on the image, and choose the <code>Set as Wallpaper...</code> option. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/08/Set-third-party-wallpaper-in-budgie-desktop.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1117" height="708" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/08/Set-third-party-wallpaper-in-budgie-desktop.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/08/Set-third-party-wallpaper-in-budgie-desktop.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/08/Set-third-party-wallpaper-in-budgie-desktop.png 1117w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><h2 id="2-change-the-desktop-theme-icons-and-cursor-theme"> 2. Change the desktop theme, icons, and cursor theme</h2><p> Traditionally, we download themes from the web, extract the downloaded file, and move files to the respective directory to <a href="https://itsfoss.com/install-themes-ubuntu/" rel="noreferrer">apply the theme on Linux</a> .</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"> <a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://itsfoss.com/install-themes-ubuntu/"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">How to Install Themes in Ubuntu Linux</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-description">This beginner&#39;s guide shows you how to install themes in Ubuntu. The tutorial covers the installation of icon themes, cursor themes, GTK themes and GNOME Shell themes.</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w256h256/2022/12/android-chrome-192x192.png" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux"><span class="kg-bookmark-author">这是 FOSS</span> <span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">Abhishek Prakash</span></div></div> <div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/03/install-theme-ubuntu.png" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux"></div></a></figure><p> But that takes a while and may not be the quickest way to do it. You are free to explore it above if you are curious.</p><p> And that&#39;s where the <strong>ocs-url</strong> tool comes into play.</p><p> A tool that will install any theme (from portals like <em>gnome-look.org</em> ) with a single click.</p><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-green"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 💡</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> Gnome-look.org and pling.com are a network of sites by <a href="https://www.opendesktop.org/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">Opendesktop.org</a> to help you find themes, wallpapers, icons, and other goodies in a single place.<br><br> It is in no way officially affiliated with any desktop environment.</div></div><p> But the sad part is that it is not available in the package manager of any Linux distribution, which means you have to install it on your system manually.</p><p> So first, go to the <a href="https://www.opendesktop.org/p/1136805/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">official download page of the ocs-url</a> , go to the <code>Files</code> tab, and download packages for your system: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/08/Download-ocs-url-in-budgie.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1056" height="407" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/08/Download-ocs-url-in-budgie.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/08/Download-ocs-url-in-budgie.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/08/Download-ocs-url-in-budgie.png 1056w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Once done, open your terminal and change the directory where the file was downloaded. For the most users, it will be the <code>Downloads</code> directory:</p><pre> <code>cd Downloads</code></pre><p> Now, use the following command for your Linux distro:</p><p> <strong>For Ubuntu:</strong></p><pre> <code>sudo dpkg -i ocs-url*.deb</code></pre><p> <strong>For Fedora:</strong></p><pre> <code>sudo dnf install qt5-qtbase qt5-qtbase-gui qt5-qtsvg qt5-qtdeclarative qt5-qtquickcontrols &amp;&amp; sudo rpm -i ocs-url*.rpm</code></pre><p> <strong>For Arch:</strong></p><pre> <code>sudo pacman -S qt5-base qt5-svg qt5-declarative qt5-quickcontrols &amp;&amp; sudo pacman -U ocs-url*.pkg.tar.xz</code></pre><p> <strong>For openSUSE:</strong></p><pre> <code>sudo zypper install libQt5Svg5 libqt5-qtquickcontrols &amp;&amp; sudo rpm -i ocs-url*.rpm</code></pre><p> Now, let&#39;s take a look at how you install system themes, icons, and cursor themes.</p><h3 id="change-system-theme"> Change system theme</h3><p> To change the system theme, first, visit the <a href="https://www.gnome-look.org/browse?cat=135&amp;ord=latest&amp;ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">Gnome Look</a> portal and select your preferred theme (you can choose between GTK 3 and 4 themes): </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Open-gnome-look-to-install-system-themes-in-budgie-desktop.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1470" height="638" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Open-gnome-look-to-install-system-themes-in-budgie-desktop.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/Open-gnome-look-to-install-system-themes-in-budgie-desktop.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Open-gnome-look-to-install-system-themes-in-budgie-desktop.png 1470w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Decide any of your favorite themes; here, I&#39;m going with the <code>Kripton</code> theme. From there, you will see the option to <code>Install</code> themes.</p><p> From here, you will have to follow two simple steps:</p><ul><li> After clicking on the <code>Install</code> button, it will show different variations of the theme. Choose one of them.</li><li> Next, it will open a prompt, there you have to hit the <code>Install</code> button: </li></ul><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Install-theme-from-ocs-url-in-budgie-dekstop.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1728" height="993" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Install-theme-from-ocs-url-in-budgie-dekstop.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/Install-theme-from-ocs-url-in-budgie-dekstop.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1600/2023/09/Install-theme-from-ocs-url-in-budgie-dekstop.png 1600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Install-theme-from-ocs-url-in-budgie-dekstop.png 1728w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> It will open ocs-url asking you whether you want to install the selected theme.</p><p> Simply press the <code>OK</code> button to install the theme: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Install-theme-from-ocs-url.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="424" height="170"></figure><p> Now, access the <strong>Budgie Desktop Settings</strong> and pick the installed theme from the <code>Widget</code> option under <strong>Style</strong> section. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Change-theme-in-Budgie-desktop-using-the-budgie-desktop-settings-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="920" height="634" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Change-theme-in-Budgie-desktop-using-the-budgie-desktop-settings-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Change-theme-in-Budgie-desktop-using-the-budgie-desktop-settings-1.png 920w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><h3 id="change-icons"> Change icons</h3><p> To change icons, <a href="https://www.gnome-look.org/browse?cat=132&amp;ord=latest&amp;ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">visit the Icon section of the Gnome-look</a> portal, and find/search for the icon that suits you the best: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Download-icons-for-budgie-desktop.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1136" height="638" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Download-icons-for-budgie-desktop.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/Download-icons-for-budgie-desktop.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Download-icons-for-budgie-desktop.png 1136w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Once you find that perfect icon, you will find two options there: Download and Install. Click on the <code>Install</code> button.</p><p> You may find multiple icons, but in most cases there will only be one. Click on that option, it will open a prompt. Again, hit the <code>Install</code> button: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Install-icons-for-budgie-desktop-environment.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1870" height="1034" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Install-icons-for-budgie-desktop-environment.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/Install-icons-for-budgie-desktop-environment.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1600/2023/09/Install-icons-for-budgie-desktop-environment.png 1600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Install-icons-for-budgie-desktop-environment.png 1870w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Soon, you&#39;ll see a prompt from ocs-url asking whether you want to install the selected icon pack or not. Hit the <code>OK</code> button to install the icon pack: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Use-ocs-url-to-install-icons-in-budgie-desktop-environment.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="424" height="170"></figure><p> Next, open the <strong>Budgie Desktop Settings</strong> and from the icons, you can select the recently installed icons (I went with the elementary-kde option): </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Select-icon-to-customize-the-budgie-desktop-from-budgie-desktop-settings.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="920" height="608" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Select-icon-to-customize-the-budgie-desktop-from-budgie-desktop-settings.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Select-icon-to-customize-the-budgie-desktop-from-budgie-desktop-settings.png 920w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><h3 id="change-cursor-theme"> Change cursor theme</h3><p> Similar to the above, <a href="https://www.gnome-look.org/browse?cat=107&amp;ord=latest&amp;ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">visit the Gnome Look&#39;s cursor icon section</a> to find the most suitable cursor theme for you: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Download-cursor-icons-for-budgie-desktop.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1362" height="638" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Download-cursor-icons-for-budgie-desktop.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/Download-cursor-icons-for-budgie-desktop.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Download-cursor-icons-for-budgie-desktop.png 1362w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Once you find the perfect cursor theme, click on the option, and you will see the option to install the selected cursor theme.</p><p> It will open a prompt and there, click again on the installation button: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Install-cursor-icons-for-the-budgie-desktop-environment.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1818" height="1038" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Install-cursor-icons-for-the-budgie-desktop-environment.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/Install-cursor-icons-for-the-budgie-desktop-environment.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1600/2023/09/Install-cursor-icons-for-the-budgie-desktop-environment.png 1600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Install-cursor-icons-for-the-budgie-desktop-environment.png 1818w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> You will see a prompt from the ocs-url to install the cursor theme. All you have to do is press the <code>OK</code> button to start the installation: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Install-the-cursor-icon-theme-in-budgie-desktop-environment-using-the-ocs-url.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="424" height="170"></figure><p> Once done, open the Budgie Desktop Settings and choose the cursor theme from the <code>Cursors</code> : </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Select-the-cursor-icon-theme-from-the-budgie-desktop-settings-for-custoomizing-the-budgie-desktop-environment.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="984" height="664" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Select-the-cursor-icon-theme-from-the-budgie-desktop-settings-for-custoomizing-the-budgie-desktop-environment.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Select-the-cursor-icon-theme-from-the-budgie-desktop-settings-for-custoomizing-the-budgie-desktop-environment.png 984w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><h2 id="3-customize-the-panel-in-budgie-desktop"> 3. Customize the panel in Budgie Desktop</h2><p> Depending on the Linux distro, the position for the panel may differ. For instance, you could be using Solus Budgie or Ubuntu Budgie.</p><p> To access the settings for the panel, open the Budgie Desktop Settings, and from there you will find the settings for the panel: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Access-budgie-desktop-panel-settings.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="946" height="664" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Access-budgie-desktop-panel-settings.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Access-budgie-desktop-panel-settings.png 946w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> As you can see, it shows the enabled applets on the panel in three sections:<br><br> <strong>Start</strong> (extreme left), <strong>Center</strong> , and <strong>End</strong> (extreme right).</p><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-blue"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 📋</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> Remember, each applet has multiple options so you can also configure them individually.</div></div><p> You can adjust between them. For example, here, I moved the clock to the left side as it suits my workflow much better: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Move-applets-in-budgie-desktop.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1145" height="687" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Move-applets-in-budgie-desktop.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/Move-applets-in-budgie-desktop.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Move-applets-in-budgie-desktop.png 1145w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>要移动小程序，您只需选择小程序并使用<strong>小程序列表上方的向上和向下箭头按钮即可。</strong></p><p> If you want to remove the applet, just select the applet and use the delete button: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Delete-applet-from-the-panel.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="946" height="664" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Delete-applet-from-the-panel.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Delete-applet-from-the-panel.png 946w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> To add more applets, there is an option to add applet with the <code>+</code> icon. Simply press the button, and it will list all the available applets to you.</p><p> Once you find a useful applet, select the applet and click on the <code>Add</code> button: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Add-applet-in-budgie-desktop-environment.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1327" height="800" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Add-applet-in-budgie-desktop-environment.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/Add-applet-in-budgie-desktop-environment.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Add-applet-in-budgie-desktop-environment.png 1327w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> If you want to make the panel transparent, add shadows, increase/decrease space between applets, then go to the settings menu as shown below: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Tweak-panel-of-the-budgie-desktop.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="955" height="664" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Tweak-panel-of-the-budgie-desktop.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Tweak-panel-of-the-budgie-desktop.png 955w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> For example, here, I made my panel transparent and added shadows to make it look pleasant: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Add-transparency-and-shadows-in-budgie-desktop-panel-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="993" height="664" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Add-transparency-and-shadows-in-budgie-desktop-panel-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Add-transparency-and-shadows-in-budgie-desktop-panel-1.png 993w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><h2 id="4-customize-the-dock-in-the-budgie-desktop"> 4. Customize the dock in the Budgie Desktop</h2><p> In this section, I will walk you through the following ways to make your dock look appealing and functional:</p><ul><li> Changing the theme of the dock</li><li> Adding docklets to add more features to the dock</li></ul><h3 id="change-the-theme-of-the-dock"> Change the theme of the dock</h3><p> Sorry, but the ocs-url tool won&#39;t help you change the theme of the dock, so the only way you are left with it is the manual way!</p><p> First, <a href="https://www.gnome-look.org/browse?cat=273&amp;ord=latest&amp;ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">visit the Gnome Look&#39;s Plank theme</a> section and download any of your favorite plank dock themes.</p><p> Here, I went for the Monterey theme to mimic macOS (dark-inline version): </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Download-theme-for-the-plank-dock-in-budgie-desktop-environment.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1794" height="1178" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Download-theme-for-the-plank-dock-in-budgie-desktop-environment.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/Download-theme-for-the-plank-dock-in-budgie-desktop-environment.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1600/2023/09/Download-theme-for-the-plank-dock-in-budgie-desktop-environment.png 1600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Download-theme-for-the-plank-dock-in-budgie-desktop-environment.png 1794w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Now, open the terminal and navigate to where the theme was downloaded.</p><p> For most users, it will be the <code>Downloads</code> directory:</p><pre> <code>cd ~/Downloads</code></pre><p> Now, <a href="https://itsfoss.com/unzip-linux/" rel="noreferrer">use the unzip command</a> to extract files to the <code>.local/share/plank/themes/</code> :</p><pre> <code>unzip &lt;theme_name.zip>; -d .local/share/plank/themes/</code></pre><p> In my case, it looked like this:</p><pre> <code>unzip Monterey-Dark-inline.zip -d ~/.local/share/plank/themes/</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/extract-plank-dock-themes-in-budgie-desktop.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="847" height="178" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/extract-plank-dock-themes-in-budgie-desktop.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/extract-plank-dock-themes-in-budgie-desktop.png 847w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Next, open the <code>Plank preferences</code> and change to the recently installed theme.</p><p> I changed mine to <code>Monterey -Dark inline</code> : </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Change-theme-in-plank-dock-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="779" height="497" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Change-theme-in-plank-dock-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Change-theme-in-plank-dock-1.png 779w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><h3 id="add-docklets-to-have-more-features"> Add docklets to have more features</h3><p> Think of docklets as applets but for the dock but unlike applets, you are not given many options.</p><p> To add/remove docklets, first, open the <code>Plank preferences</code> and go to the <code>Docklets</code> menu to list the available options: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Docklets-in-Plank-dock.png" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="708" height="413" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Docklets-in-Plank-dock.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Docklets-in-Plank-dock.png 708w"></figure><p> Now, if you want to add docklets, simply drag them to the dock: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Add-docklets-in-Plank-dock-budgie-desktop-configuration.gif" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="657" height="432" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Add-docklets-in-Plank-dock-budgie-desktop-configuration.gif 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Add-docklets-in-Plank-dock-budgie-desktop-configuration.gif 657w"></figure><p> But what if you would like to remove the added docklets?</p><p> Well, that&#39;s pretty simple! Just drag them out of the dock and they will be removed: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Remove-docklets-from-the-plank-budgie-desktop.gif" class="kg-image" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux" loading="lazy" width="853" height="432" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Remove-docklets-from-the-plank-budgie-desktop.gif 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Remove-docklets-from-the-plank-budgie-desktop.gif 853w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><h2 id="ready-to-get-started-with-budgie"> Ready to Get Started With Budgie?</h2><p> Sure, you can always install a Linux distribution with Budgie desktop environment baked in—for convenience.</p><p> However, you can also choose to <a href="https://itsfoss.com/install-budgie-ubuntu/" rel="noreferrer">install Budgie</a> on your existing distro, such as Ubuntu:</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"> <a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://itsfoss.com/install-budgie-ubuntu/"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">How to Install Budgie Desktop on Ubuntu</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-description">Budgie is a modern, alternative take on GNOME. Learn to install the Budgie desktop environment on Ubuntu.</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w256h256/2022/12/android-chrome-192x192.png" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux"><span class="kg-bookmark-author">这是 FOSS</span> <span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">Abhishek Prakash</span></div></div> <div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/wordpress/2019/04/install-budgie-ubuntu.png" alt="4 Incredibly Simple Ways to Customize Budgie Desktop in Linux"></div></a></figure><p> For this tutorial, I utilized Ubuntu Budgie. The steps work for Budgie desktop no matter the distribution you use.</p><p> <em>💬 How do you customize your Budgie desktop experience? Do you want to add any tips to this article? Share your experiences in the comments down below.</em></p> ;
